\begin_layout Section
Interpreting 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{j}$
\end_inset

's
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Get Existential: What is Regression?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You theorize:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}x1_{i}+\beta_{2}x2_{i}+...+\beta_{k}xk_{i}+e_{i}\,\,\,\,\,\, i=1,...,N\label{ols}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
and through __________ procedure, you make estimates 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{j}$
\end_inset

 with which to calculate predicted values:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{y}_{i}=\widehat{\beta}_{0}+\widehat{\beta}_{1}x1_{i}+\widehat{\beta}_{2}x2_{i}+...+\widehat{\beta}_{k}xk_{i}\,\,\,\,\,\, i=1,...,N\label{predict}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Everything else we do should be understood through this lens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Yes, But What Do You DO with a Regression?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compare 2 cases, with inputs 
\begin_inset Formula $(x1_{0},x2_{0},\ldots,xk_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(x1_{1},x2_{1},\dots,xk_{1})$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The predicted values 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{y_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{y_{1}}$
\end_inset

 are different, some of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x's$
\end_inset

 matter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The focus is on developing substantively interesting comparisons!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We'd like to narrow our attention down, to concentrate on one predictor
 at a time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(x1_{0},x2_{0},\ldots,xk_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(x1_{0},x2_{1},\dots,xk_{0})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They only differ on 
\begin_inset Formula $x2$
\end_inset

, so the difference between predictions must be attributable to the change
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout BeginFrame
Substantively Interesting 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

partial regression coefficients
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Linear formula: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

other things equal, a 1 unit increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{i}$
\end_inset

 causes an estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 unit increase in the predicted value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No reason to say researcher can only compare variables by changing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one unit at a time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Know the problem's context, pick interesting values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{1}$
\end_inset

 for comparison.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
x2 represents 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

last year school
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{0}=$
\end_inset

8th grade, 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{1}=$
\end_inset

high school 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
x2 represents income, 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{0}=$
\end_inset

$10,000, 
\begin_inset Formula $x2_{1}=$
\end_inset

 $100,000
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout BeginFrame
Linear and Continuous X's: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Maybe the calculus says it best:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial y}{\partial x2}=\hat{\beta}_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But there's no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute scale
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x's$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are numerically re-scaled, then the coefficients will change too.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
