\begin_layout BeginFrame
Another School of Thought: Try to Convert Variables to a Common Metric
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Preferred by psychologists (and many sociologists)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A standardized variable is calculated like so:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
standardized\, y_{i}=\frac{y_{i}-Observed\, mean\mbox{\ensuremath{(y_{i})}}}{Observed\, Std.Dev.(y_{i})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I'm not calling that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Z score
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 score presumes we know the TRUE mean and standard deviation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By definition, all standardized variables have a mean of 0 and a standard
 deviation of 1.
 See why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What is the common metric with standardized variables? (I'm asking, seriously)
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Use Standardized Variables in Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X1_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X2_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X3_{i}$
\end_inset

 by standardized variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A standardized regression is like so:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{y_{i}-\bar{y}}{s_{y}}\right)=\beta_{1}^{st}\left(\frac{X1_{i}-\overline{X1}}{s_{X1}}\right)+\beta_{2}^{st}\left(\frac{X2_{i}-\overline{X2}}{s_{X2}}\right)+\beta_{3}^{st}\left(\frac{X3_{i}-\overline{X3}}{s_{X3}}\right)+u_{i}\label{standardized}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The estimated coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{st}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standardized regression coefficients
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Coefficients we discussed until now are un-standardized parameter estimates,
 which in past I have labeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

, just to avoid confusion with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Betas
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 slang
\end_layout

