\begin_layout Standard
Gary King's fine essay 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How not to lie with statistics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 explores many other flaws in the use of standardized coefficients.
 I'll summarize a couple of the points I found most persuasive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Problem: We estimate by the sample standard deviation, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{X1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{X2}$
\end_inset

 .
 But we act 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

as if
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 they were 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 values.
 (We don't know 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X1}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X2}$
\end_inset

, ...)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose unstandardized 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}=\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Two variables have same effect.
 And they are measured on the same scale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If observed std.dev.
 are different, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x1}\neq s_{x2}$
\end_inset

, that will cause 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}^{st}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}^{st}$
\end_inset

 to differ.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Along those lines, take a subset of the data.
 Even if the relationship is the same, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{st}$
\end_inset

 will flop about because estimated standard deviations change..
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
betas are not comparable across regressions.
 and they are not comparable within regressions.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
